## Attack Chain Summary

1. Stored XSS via User-Agent header
2. Payload stored in database
3. Admin views page → payload executed
4. New admin account created
5. Login as new admin
6. Upload malicious plugin
7. Execute commands via web shell
8. Upgrade to reverse shell
9. Retrieve flag

---

## Key Concepts

* Stored XSS can lead to full account compromise
* JavaScript can automate privileged actions using authenticated sessions
* WordPress plugin upload can lead to remote code execution
* Web shells provide limited access and should be upgraded
* Reverse shells provide better interaction and control
* The www-data user typically runs web services on Linux systems

---

## Tools Used

* curl → send requests and execute commands
* netcat → reverse shell listener
* zip → package plugin
* browser → trigger XSS

---

## Summary

This lab demonstrated how a Stored XSS vulnerability can escalate into full system compromise by chaining:

* client-side exploitation
* privilege escalation (admin creation)
* remote code execution
* interactive shell access

